br />charging at you in excess of 100 mph". Doubt no more,<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br />PS. Fairy penguins are _small_. Like less than 2 feet tall and weighing in<br />at a whopping 2 pounds. The thought of a mob of angry fairy penguins<br />mauling tourists fairly boggles the mind..<br /><br />---<br />On Thu, 13 Nov 1997, Andrew Humphrey wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; Howdy,<br />&gt; <br />&gt; 	Seeing as you are the ``owner'' of a penguin at some zoo somewhere or <br />&gt; other I figured that this was important information that you should probably<br />&gt; be made aware of.  If you ever go visit it, I suggest you remember the <br />&gt; minimum safe distance :-)<br />&gt; <br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; The following is an extract from<br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; <a href="http://www.bigbenpublishing.com.au/victoria/info_animals.html">http://www.bigbenpublishing.com.au/victoria/info_animals.html</a><br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; Fairy Penguins<br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; Although it's not widely reported for fear of jeopardising tourism, fairy <br />&gt; &gt; penguins have developed some very antisocial behaviour as a result of <br />&gt; &gt; continuous close contact with humans. <br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; Their sensitivity to photographic flashes has long been known. In recent <br />&gt; &gt; years there have been isolated attacks where an unsuspecting tourist was <br />&gt; &gt; mauled by half a dozen or more fairy penguins after using a flash gun to <br />&gt; &gt; photograph them at dusk. <br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; &gt; While they may be flightless, during such attacks they have been seen to <br />&gt; &gt; jump as far as three metres to pounce on their victim. Beware penguins with <br />&gt; &gt; attitudes!!! <br />&gt; &gt; <br />&gt; <br />&gt; Cheers,<br />&gt; Andrew Humphrey<br />&gt; andrew&#64;bofh.asn.au<br />&gt; <br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-